40:04.512 --> 40:19.453
What we're really talking about here is, again, the power of literature, and it's very interesting that both people from the left, liberal wing, politically, and people from the right, often very, very conservative, have embraced this program.

40:20.395 --> 40:32.969
And I had a sentence at two a time about, you know, these Texas judges were willing, and in many cases have, actually, they take capital cases and send people to their death.

40:34.531 --> 40:38.856
And those are the same judges who are embracing this program.

40:39.136 --> 40:47.466
And they believe, and probably more deeply than some of the judges in Massachusetts who are involved with this, that somehow,

40:48.779 --> 40:52.945
Our story, our literature can affect some kind of salvation.

40:53.125 --> 40:54.467
I think that's the way they're thinking about this.

40:55.389 --> 41:03.040
But they, from the far right, embrace it just as well as the other people, you know, liberal side.

41:03.060 --> 41:07.607
I've always believed literature really does transcend the politics anyway.

41:07.627 --> 41:15.779
It's not about something, the universal quality of the literature and the complexity of it.

41:15.799 --> 41:17.622
Listen, guys, I'm going to head back to

41:18.158 --> 41:18.644
All right.

41:18.786 --> 41:19.171
Oh, good.

